Just a few days ago I came across this photo of myself from two years ago. My immediate thought was ‚ÄúWow, you do NOT look like that now.‚Äù My mind immediately ran back to that day to remember what I did to stay so thin back then so I could start doing that same routine again now to replicate that body. (WHAT?!?!). Truth: I thought I had so much work ‚Äúleft to do to get fit‚Äù when I had this body, and there wasn‚Äôt hardly a moment where I didn‚Äôt look in the mirror hoping to see something smaller, something more toned, something different. Reality: I have worked out just as hard, just as often, and stayed just as disciplined (if not more) than I did then. I lift heavier weights that have made my arms bigger, I have done more pushups that have made my chest bigger, and done more squats to add a little more curve to this photo. I‚Äôve also stopped running on a hurt knee and stopped taking a bite of a donut just to throw it in the trash out of shame on the second bite. I have no idea how my current body really compares to this selfie because I have vowed not to weigh myself since this day where I celebrated 45 lbs of weight loss. What I do know is that I hope in two more years I am not celebrating ‚Äúpounds lost‚Äù or ‚Äúsize worn‚Äù- instead celebrating ‚Äúfulfilling exercise‚Äù and ‚Äúmeals enjoyed‚Äù without guilt. Cheers to a 2020 filled with celebrating accomplishments and loving everything our bodies DO for us versus what we THINK they should look like based on media standards. Loving ourselves can be a daily struggle for women (and men!) but just know that I‚Äôm right here with you. And let‚Äôs compliment each other on our strength and grit and intelligence instead of on the size of our lulu‚Äôs. #loveyourself #youareenough #normalizenormalbodies #strongwomen

2,132. After my first job out of college in 2013, and years of ignoring my health, I made a commitment to myself to be active & work out at least 20 minutes a day, 5x a week, every week. No excuses. In 2014, I upped it to 6x a week - taking off days when I was sick and doing doubles to make up for them in my stronger days to follow. My proudest accomplishment reflecting on the last decade - I never let anything get in the way of my health. Sometimes that meant running on the beach at 7AM on vacation or going to sculpt after a lonnng night of celebrating something. Seven years, 2,132 workouts. Here‚Äôs to 3,000 more in the 2020s. You CAN commit to moving 6 days a week, even if it‚Äôs just a walk with your dog or a 20 minute HIIT workout in your hotel room! Believe in yourself. And guess what - I had plenty of fun in there too. No regrets. All In. üí™üèª What are you working on in 2020?

Finding challenges in the journey of constant ‚ÄúSvadhyaya‚Äù, self-study, these days. Knowing that finding ‚ÄúSantosha‚Äù, contentment, right where I am, is the key to happiness. That a daily gratitude practice allows me to find this. That ‚ÄúAparigraha‚Äù, not wanting to have or have accomplished what my neighbor has, is the best way to free the mind of comparison and simply be happy for the daily gift of life. I study the yamas and niyamas daily, and yet every day I evaluate myself as a fundraiser/employee/yoga teacher/pet mom/partner/friend/daughter/plantmom/student/ETC. and look for faults, the areas that I am not succeeding, the places where I am falling short. I fixate and I rob myself of the joy of so many hours in the name of negativity. Friends, maybe like me you need a reminder that this is a *practice* for a reason. We are all a daily work in progress. If we want to be the best version of ourselves, we need to first lay the groundwork - but never forget to enjoy the journey or the process. Enjoy your passions, and allow time and space to bring you what is transformational. You are exactly where you need to be. >>> Does this resonate with you?
